post_text:
Phoenix Week is next week and here's what you need to know!

Students are asked to come to school IN PERSON for a one day orientation - this will include:
•Time in all 8 of students’ classes to learn about procedures, expectations, and technology requirements.
•Pick up of Chromebooks, text books, supply kits - anything needed for classes during the first quarter.
•Social distancing (¼ of our student body each day) with full sanitation procedures.
•Breakfast will be available from 7:30, students must arrive by 7:50am
•Students who are not able to attend due to illness, exposure, or family concerns will be able to have a family member pick up Chromebooks on their behalf - please contact the school for more information.

These will be ready to go at the beginning of the 2020-21 school year!

post_text: Sadly, prom isn’t happening this weekend but GCAA Student Media wants to know what you would’ve worn.
shared_text:
GCAA Student Media
April 28 at 12:17 PM ·

Hello class of 2020!

As many of you are probably aware, this weekend was supposed to be Prom, and given our current situation, we’re unable to show off the new outfits we bought during or before quarantine. While you’re unable to wear your outfits to Prom, there’s still a way for you to show off your outfits: send a picture of you wearing your Prom outfit to editors@gcaatoday.com! We’ll use your pictures on a spread in the Senior Magazine which will also include senior superlatives, senior quotes, and more! So if you’re interested in strutting your stuff, even if it’s just through a picture, we’ll be happy to put it in the magazine for everyone to see. Please make sure to include in your email what name you prefer to go by, and make sure that the pictures are of good quality. You will only have up to May 5th to turn in your pictures, or else we won’t be able to use them in the magazine. Thank you very much, and stay healthy!

Sincerely,
GCAA Student Media Staff

post_text: The current population rate for the US census in the City of St. Louis is only 38%. The 2020 census count impacts the federal funds that communities receive each year for programs and services that are critical for schools, students, and younger children such as: Special Education, free and reduced-price school lunches, food assistance, classroom technology, after school programs and more. Therefore, if we can increase participation in the US Census 2020, in turn it will benefit our schools and students. Respond now at: my2020census.gov

Shout out to Ms. Shelby for successfully hosting The Mad City Money Financial Reality Simulation in conjunction with Sterling Bank and Lindenwood University for Life after High School and Personal Finance students.

The Mad City Money Financial Reality Simulation is an effective experiential-learning tool for teaching personal finance concepts and life skills to students. Through the school-based simulation, students discover the impact of their decisions, learn important financial concepts and practice money management skills in a creative role-playing activity.

Students develop financial skills by getting a taste of the real world as they take on the role of an adult – complete with occupation, salary, family, student loan and credit card debts, and medical insurance payments. 💲

S/O to Photography students, Jordan Britt & Nakia Artis, for these awesome shots! 📷

Last week one of our teachers, Mr. Vaccaro, picked up a bunch of instruments donated to the music department by the organization called Play It Forward~STL . Their purpose is to provide instruments and resources to schools like ours and other situations where it provides someone the ability to play music where they otherwise couldn’t. Thank you Play It Forward~STL for this generous donation, our GCAA students will put these instruments to good use!

Here is a picture of the haul we got from them!
